he novel role pedagogical interventions played in confronting the past, as well as critical theory's limits in dealing with conflict in a world where formerly clear-cut notions of victims and perpetrators are blurred. While Jansen originally set out simply to convey a story of how white students changed under the leadership of a diverse group of senior academics, Knowledge in the Blood ultimately became an unexpected account of how these students in turn changed him. The impact of this book's unique, wide-ranging insights in dealing with racial and ethnic divisions will be felt far beyond the borders of South Africa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAfrikaner studentszSouth AfricaxAttitudes. 0aCollege integrationzSouth Africa. 0aCollege students, WhitezSouth AfricaxAttitudes. 0aEducational changezSouth Africa. 0aPost-apartheid erazSouth Africa. 0aRacism in higher educationzSouth Africa. 7aEDUCATION / Leadership.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477116040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804771160423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804771160.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles